I'm trying to take stab at adding dominant-baseline handling (although Rust isn't my strong suit). I've added most of the scaffolding for `dominant-baseline` property handling and am now trying to figure out how to get the font metrics needed. As a first (hacky) test I get the `FontDescription` from the `Layout` (or `Context` if not set), but it appears the values for the font set don't make much sense. E.g. https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/librsvg/-/blob/main/rsvg/src/text.rs?ref_type=heads#L201:

```
            let layout = mspan.layout.clone();
            let layout_size = mspan.layout_size;
            let context = layout.context();
            let font_description = if layout.font_description().is_none() { context.font_description() } else { layout.font_description() };
            println!("font: {}, size {}", font_description.as_ref().unwrap().family().unwrap().as_str(),
                font_description.as_ref().unwrap().size());
            let font_metrics = context.metrics(font_description.as_ref(), context.language().as_ref());
```

The font info printed is always "font: serif, size 12288", even though I have `<text>` with font-family "Arial" and "Impact" in the .svg I'm testing with. The corresponding metrics then (unsurprisingly) don't seem to work very well. 

> To do this well, librsvg should obtain the individual `pango::Item` out of text layout, instead of using just the higher-level `pango::Layout`. You can get the individual font of each item, I think.

@federico I don't immediately see how to get `Item`'s out of the `Layout`, can you give a hint? Edit: ah, seems `Item`'s get produced by `itemize()`, but that means going back to the underlying text?

Edit 2: added `itemize()` in `MeasuredSpan.from_span()` to store the items in `MeasuredSpan` gives at least access to them. But I still don't see how to get more font data than ascent/descent, as @12Me21 indicated earlier.

